Note: ============================================================================
Note: ERLANG TRANSLATION TESTS - Production Translation Test Suite
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Comprehensive tests for Erlang lexer, parser, translator, generator, emitter
Note: Tests: tokenization, parsing, Erlang→HIR, HIR→Erlang, round-trip
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_lexer.runa" as ErlangLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_parser.runa" as ErlangParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_to_hir.runa" as ErlangToHir
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/erlang/hir_to_erlang.runa" as HirToErlang
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_printer.runa" as ErlangEmitter
Note: ============================================================================
Note: TEST FRAMEWORK
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-test outcome record. Each test_* proc returns one of these
so the harness can distinguish pass/fail and capture a diagnostic
message on failure without parsing stdout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
test_name carries the human-readable label; passed is the boolean
verdict; error_message is "" on success and a short reason string
on failure. The struct is value-typed (returned by value, not by
handle) so each test creates a fresh result.
@End Implementation

Type called "TestResult":
    test_name as String
    passed as Boolean
    error_message as String
End Type

Note: Local stand-ins for the HIR module/function records the erlang_to_hir
Note: translator returns. The canonical HIR types live in hir.runa but use
Note: opaque HIRNode + child-list traversal; until the test pipeline is
Note: rewritten against that idiom these local types let the test bodies
Note: compile against the schema they expect.
@Reasoning:
Local stand-in for the canonical HIR Module record. The canonical
HIR types in hir.runa use opaque HIRNode + child-list traversal; this
test file pre-dates that refactor and uses a typed module/function
struct so tests can dot-access fields directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single field: a list of HIRFunctionRecord. Module-level attributes
(name, exports, etc.) are not tracked at this layer because the
tests focus on the function payload.
@End Implementation

Type called "HIRModuleRecord":
    functions as List[HIRFunctionRecord]
End Type

@Reasoning:
Local stand-in for the canonical HIR Function record. Same rationale
as HIRModuleRecord: pre-canonical-refactor struct shape used by
test bodies. body is an Integer (handle to opaque HIR body node)
rather than a typed expression tree.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
name carries the function identifier; body holds an opaque handle to
the HIR for the body expression. Parameter list and arity tracking
not modeled here because tests check name+presence rather than
shape.
@End Implementation

Type called "HIRFunctionRecord":
    name as String
    body as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Container for an entire test phase (lexer, parser, translator,
etc.) bundling the suite label, list of individual TestResults,
and aggregate pass/fail counters. Counters are maintained in
sync with results.length by add_test_result.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
suite_name labels the phase. results holds every TestResult appended
via add_test_result. passed_count and failed_count are maintained
in-line so report_test_suite doesn't have to recount.
@End Implementation

Type called "TestSuite":
    suite_name as String
    results as List[TestResult]
    passed_count as Integer
    failed_count as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Constructor for a fresh empty TestSuite. Initializing counters at 0
and results at empty list lets add_test_result safely mutate them
without null checks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate TestSuite via "a value of type TestSuite with ...", filling
suite_name from caller, results to a list literal containing nothing,
and both counters to 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_test_suite" that takes name as String returns TestSuite:
    Return a value of type TestSuite with
        suite_name as name,
        results as a list containing nothing,
        passed_count as 0,
        failed_count as 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends a TestResult to the suite and updates the running pass/fail
counters. Centralized so individual test_* procs only need to
return a TestResult, not maintain counters themselves.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Append result to suite.results.
2. If result.passed, increment suite.passed_count else
   suite.failed_count.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_test_result" that takes suite as TestSuite, result as TestResult returns Nothing:
    Add result to end of suite.results

    If result.passed:
        Set suite.passed_count to suite.passed_count plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Set suite.failed_count to suite.failed_count plus 1
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Produces the human-readable summary string for a completed suite:
title banner, pass/fail counts, and a bullet for each failed test
with its error message. Successful tests are not enumerated so
the report stays concise in the common (all-pass) case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build "=== Test Suite: <name> ===" header line.
2. Append "Passed: N, Failed: M" line.
3. Loop For Each result in suite.results: if not passed, append
   "FAILED: <name> - <error_message>" line.
4. Return accumulated output string.
@End Implementation

Process called "report_test_suite" that takes suite as TestSuite returns String:
    Let output be "=== Test Suite: "
    Set output to output joined with suite.suite_name
    Set output to output joined with " ==="
    Set output to output joined with newline
    Set output to output joined with "Passed: "
    Set output to output joined with string representation of suite.passed_count
    Set output to output joined with ", Failed: "
    Set output to output joined with string representation of suite.failed_count
    Set output to output joined with newline

    Note: Show failed tests
    For Each result in suite.results:
        If not result.passed:
            Set output to output joined with "FAILED: "
            Set output to output joined with result.test_name
            Set output to output joined with " - "
            Set output to output joined with result.error_message
            Set output to output joined with newline
        End If
    End For

    Return output
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LEXER TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the Erlang lexer recognizes both bare atoms (hello, ok,
error) and quoted atoms ('quoted atom'). Quoted form is needed for
atom names containing spaces or starting with capitals.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Lex `hello world 'quoted atom' ok error true false`. Assert >= 6
tokens and first token type == TOKEN_ATOM.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Six atoms (bare + quoted) -> length >= 6 and first is atom, passed
- Length < 6 -> "Expected at least 6 tokens" failure
- First token misclassified -> "First token should be ATOM" failure
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_atoms" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "hello world 'quoted atom' ok error true false"

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Note: Check token count
    If length of lexer.tokens is less than 6:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Lexer Atoms",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected at least 6 tokens"
    End If

    Note: Check first token is atom
    If lexer.tokens at index 0 is not equal to TOKEN_ATOM:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Lexer Atoms",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "First token should be ATOM"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Lexer Atoms",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies Erlang variable tokenization: uppercase-starting names (X,
Var), underscore-prefixed unused variable (_Ignored), and mixed
(Name123). Capital-vs-lowercase first letter distinguishes Variable
from Atom in Erlang grammar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Lex "X Var _Ignored Name123". Assert tokens classify as VARIABLE.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- 4 variables -> all classify as VARIABLE, passed
- Lexer classifies "X" as atom -> "First token should be VARIABLE" fails
- Lexer rejects "_Ignored" -> token count drops
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_variables" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "X Var _Ignored Name123"

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Note: All should be variables
    If length of lexer.tokens is less than 4:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Lexer Variables",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected at least 4 tokens"
    End If

    For Each token in lexer.tokens:
        If token is not equal to TOKEN_VARIABLE and token is not equal to TOKEN_EOF:
            Return a value of type TestResult with
                test_name as "Lexer Variables",
                passed as false,
                error_message as "All tokens should be VARIABLE"
        End If
    End For

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Lexer Variables",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies Erlang number literals: integer, float, and Erlang-specific
base-prefix syntax (16#FF for hex, 2#1010 for binary).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Lex a string with multiple numeric forms; assert each tokenizes
as a number.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Numeric forms -> all NUMBER tokens, passed
- Lexer fails on "16#FF" notation -> token count drops or wrong type
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_numbers" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "123 3.14 16#FF 2#1010 8#77"

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Note: Check we have number tokens
    If length of lexer.tokens is less than 5:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Lexer Numbers",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected at least 5 tokens"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Lexer Numbers",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies Erlang operators including the unique ones: arrow (->),
match (==), exact-match (=:=), and pipe (|) for list cons.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Lex Erlang operator soup; assert tokens classify correctly.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All operators tokenize -> passed
- Lexer fails on "=:=" -> wrong tokens or count
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_operators" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "+ - * / == =:= =/= ! -> =>"

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Note: Check we have operator tokens
    If length of lexer.tokens is less than 8:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Lexer Operators",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected at least 8 tokens"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Lexer Operators",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies Erlang binary literal syntax (<<...>>). Binary literals
are Erlang-specific and require the lexer to recognize << and >>
as dedicated bracket tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Lex a string with binary literal syntax; assert tokens include
the bracket and field tokens.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "<<1, 2, 3>>" -> tokens include binary brackets, passed
- Lexer fuses "<<" as two LT tokens -> shape wrong
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_binary_syntax" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "<< 1, 2, 3 >>"

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Note: Check for binary tokens
    If lexer.tokens at index 0 is not equal to TOKEN_LBIN:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Lexer Binary Syntax",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected TOKEN_LBIN"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Lexer Binary Syntax",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PARSER TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles a simple Erlang function clause:
"add(X, Y) -> X + Y." with terminator period. Catches a regression
where the parser fails on the canonical function definition form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse "add(X, Y) -> X + Y.", assert the resulting AST contains a
function node with name "add" and two parameters.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "add(X, Y) -> X + Y." -> AST has function "add" with 2 params, passed
- Parser missing the period -> failure
- Parser drops a parameter -> arity wrong
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_simple_function" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "double(X) -> X * 2."

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Note: Check function was parsed
    If length of module.functions is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Simple Function",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 1 function"
    End If

    Let func be module.functions at index 0 of type ErlangFunction

    If func.name is not equal to "double":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Simple Function",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Function name should be 'double'"
    End If

    If func.arity is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Simple Function",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Function arity should be 1"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Parser Simple Function",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles Erlang's pattern matching across
multiple function clauses (e.g. factorial(0) -> 1; factorial(N) ->
N * factorial(N-1).). The semicolon separates clauses; the period
terminates the function.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse multi-clause function, assert the AST contains two function
clauses with their respective patterns.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Multi-clause function -> AST has 2 clauses, passed
- Parser stops at first semicolon -> only 1 clause -> fail
- Parser misreads pattern -> wrong arity or shape
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_pattern_matching" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "head([H|T]) -> H."

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    If length of module.functions is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Pattern Matching",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 1 function"
    End If

    Let func be module.functions at index 0 of type ErlangFunction
    Let clause be func.clauses at index 0

    Note: Check pattern is list
    If length of clause.patterns is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Pattern Matching",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 1 pattern"
    End If

    Let pattern be clause.patterns at index 0

    If pattern.expr_type is not equal to "list":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Pattern Matching",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Pattern should be list"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Parser Pattern Matching",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles Erlang guard expressions (the "when"
clause appearing between pattern and body in function definitions
or case clauses). Guards have a restricted expression grammar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse a function with a guard, assert the AST includes a guard
expression attached to the clause.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "f(X) when X > 0 -> X." -> AST has guard, passed
- Parser drops the when clause -> AST lacks guard
- Parser fails on "when" keyword -> entire parse fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_guards" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "max(X, Y) when X > Y -> X; max(_, Y) -> Y."

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    If length of module.functions is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Guards",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 1 function"
    End If

    Let func be module.functions at index 0 of type ErlangFunction

    Note: Should have 2 clauses
    If length of func.clauses is not equal to 2:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Guards",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 2 clauses"
    End If

    Let clause1 be func.clauses at index 0

    Note: First clause should have guards
    If length of clause1.guards is equal to 0:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Guards",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "First clause should have guards"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Parser Guards",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles Erlang case-of expressions with multiple
pattern arms terminated by "end". Distinguishes from function-clause
pattern matching at the expression level.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse "case X of pattern1 -> body1; pattern2 -> body2 end", assert
AST has the case node with both arms.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- case-of with two arms -> AST has 2 arms, passed
- Parser fails on "end" keyword -> AST incomplete
- Parser only captures first arm -> arm count wrong
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_case_expression" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "test(X) -> case X of 0 -> zero; _ -> other end."

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    If length of module.functions is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Case Expression",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 1 function"
    End If

    Let func be module.functions at index 0 of type ErlangFunction
    Let clause be func.clauses at index 0
    Let body_expr be clause.body at index 0

    If body_expr.expr_type is not equal to "case":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Case Expression",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Body should be case expression"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Parser Case Expression",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles Erlang receive blocks (the actor-model
message-receive construct). Receive blocks have receive...after...end
form and are central to Erlang's concurrency model.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse a receive block with multiple patterns and optional after
timeout; assert AST has the receive node with the expected shape.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- receive ... end -> AST has receive node, passed
- Parser fails on "after" timeout clause -> shape wrong
- Parser only captures first pattern -> arm count wrong
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_receive_block" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "loop() -> receive stop -> ok; {msg, M} -> io:format(M), loop() after 5000 -> timeout end."

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    If length of module.functions is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Receive Block",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 1 function"
    End If

    Let func be module.functions at index 0 of type ErlangFunction
    Let clause be func.clauses at index 0
    Let body_expr be clause.body at index 0

    If body_expr.expr_type is not equal to "receive":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Receive Block",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Body should be receive expression"
    End If

    Note: Check for after clause
    If body_expr.expr_data at key "after_timeout" is equal to 0:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser Receive Block",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Receive should have after clause"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Parser Receive Block",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles Erlang list comprehensions ([Expr || Pat
<- List, Filter]). The "<-" generator and "||" lcomp opener are
Erlang-specific tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse a list comprehension, assert AST has a comprehension node
with the body expression, one or more generators, and filters.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "[X*2 || X <- L]" -> AST has lcomp with body+generator, passed
- Parser fails on "||" -> AST shape wrong
- Parser fails on "<-" -> generator missing
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_list_comprehension" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "doubles(L) -> [X * 2 || X <- L]."

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    If length of module.functions is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser List Comprehension",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 1 function"
    End If

    Let func be module.functions at index 0 of type ErlangFunction
    Let clause be func.clauses at index 0
    Let body_expr be clause.body at index 0

    If body_expr.expr_type is not equal to "list_comprehension":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Parser List Comprehension",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Body should be list comprehension"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Parser List Comprehension",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TRANSLATOR TESTS (Erlang → HIR)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the erlang_to_hir translator handles a basic function
definition end-to-end (lex -> parse -> translate). Asserts the
resulting HIR module contains the function with the correct name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Translate a simple Erlang function source. Assert the returned
HIRModuleRecord has a function whose name matches expected.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Simple function -> HIR module with named function, passed
- Translator returns null/empty module -> failure
- Function name mismatch -> failure
@End TestCases

Process called "test_translator_basic_function" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "double(X) -> X * 2."

    Note: Lex and parse
    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let erl_module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Note: Translate to HIR
    Let hir_module be translate_erlang_to_hir with erl_module of type HIRModuleRecord

    Note: Check HIR function was created
    If length of hir_module.functions is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Translator Basic Function",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 1 HIR function"
    End If

    Let hir_func be hir_module.functions at index 0 of type HIRFunctionRecord

    If hir_func.name is not equal to "double":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Translator Basic Function",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "HIR function name should be 'double'"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Translator Basic Function",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the translator handles Erlang's send (!) and receive
primitives. Message passing is Erlang's core concurrency mechanism;
the translator must preserve the semantic distinction between sync
expressions and async ! operations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Translate a function with Pid ! Msg and receive blocks; assert
the HIR captures both the send call and the receive node.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Function with send + receive -> HIR has both nodes, passed
- Translator drops send -> "Send not translated" failure
- Translator drops receive -> "Receive not translated" failure
@End TestCases

Process called "test_translator_message_passing" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "send_msg(Pid, Msg) -> Pid ! Msg."

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let erl_module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Let hir_module be translate_erlang_to_hir with erl_module of type HIRModuleRecord

    If length of hir_module.functions is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Translator Message Passing",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Expected 1 HIR function"
    End If

    Note: Check body contains send operation
    Let hir_func be hir_module.functions at index 0 of type HIRFunctionRecord

    If length of hir_func.body is equal to 0:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Translator Message Passing",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "HIR function should have body"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Translator Message Passing",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GENERATOR TESTS (HIR → Erlang)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the from-HIR generator (HIR -> Erlang) produces valid
Erlang source from a basic function HIR. Catches a regression where
the generator outputs syntactically invalid Erlang text.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build a minimal HIR function record, run the generator, then re-lex
the output and assert it tokenizes without error.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Basic function HIR -> generator output re-lexes successfully, passed
- Generator outputs garbled text -> re-lex fails
- Generator drops the period terminator -> "expected period" lex error
@End TestCases

Process called "test_generator_basic_function" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "double(X) -> X * 2."

    Note: Full pipeline: Erlang → HIR → Erlang
    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let erl_module1 be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Let hir_module be translate_erlang_to_hir with erl_module of type HIRModuleRecord1

    Let erl_module2 be generate_erlang_from_hir with hir_module

    Note: Check generated module has function
    If length of erl_module2.functions is not equal to 1:
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Generator Basic Function",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Generated module should have 1 function"
    End If

    Let func be erl_module2.functions at index 0 of type ErlangFunction

    If func.name is not equal to "double":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Generator Basic Function",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Generated function name should be 'double'"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Generator Basic Function",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EMITTER TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the emitter produces a complete Erlang module with the
-module(Name). directive at the top. Module declarations are
mandatory in Erlang source files compiled by erlc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build an HIR module record with a name and functions, run the
emitter, assert the output starts with the -module(Name). directive.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Module HIR -> output starts with "-module(", passed
- Emitter drops module directive -> "missing -module declaration"
- Emitter outputs wrong name -> directive content mismatch
@End TestCases

Process called "test_emitter_module" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "-module(test). -export([double/1]). double(X) -> X * 2."

    Note: Parse and emit
    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Let output be emit_erlang_module with module

    Note: Check output contains module name
    If not output contains "test":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Emitter Module",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Output should contain module name"
    End If

    Note: Check output contains function
    If not output contains "double":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Emitter Module",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Output should contain function name"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Emitter Module",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ROUND-TRIP TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Round-trip check: Erlang source -> HIR -> Erlang source. Asserts
the regenerated source contains the same function name and basic
structure. This catches emitter regressions on a minimal case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Lex+parse+translate a simple function, then emit, then assert key
tokens (function name, "->", terminator period) are preserved.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "double(X) -> X * 2." -> regenerated contains "double", "->", "."
- Round-trip drops "->" -> regenerated source rejected by re-parse
- Generator loses function name -> contains check fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_roundtrip_simple_function" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "double(X) -> X * 2."

    Note: Round-trip: Erlang → HIR → Erlang → Text
    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module1 be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Let hir_module be translate_erlang_to_hir with module1 of type HIRModuleRecord

    Let module2 be generate_erlang_from_hir with hir_module

    Let output be emit_erlang_module with module2

    Note: Check output is valid Erlang
    If not output contains "double":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Round-Trip Simple Function",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Output should contain 'double'"
    End If

    If not output contains "->":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Round-Trip Simple Function",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Output should contain '->'"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Round-Trip Simple Function",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Round-trip check that pattern-matched function clauses survive both
translation directions. Multi-clause functions with patterns are
much more demanding than the simple case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Translate and re-emit a multi-clause pattern-matching function;
assert key clause keywords and the semicolon separator survive.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Multi-clause function -> regenerated still has all clauses
- Generator loses second clause -> clause count differs
- Generator uses comma instead of semicolon -> re-parse fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_roundtrip_pattern_matching" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "head([H|_]) -> H."

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module1 be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Let hir_module be translate_erlang_to_hir with module1 of type HIRModuleRecord

    Let module2 be generate_erlang_from_hir with hir_module

    Let output be emit_erlang_module with module2

    Note: Check output contains list pattern
    If not output contains "head":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Round-Trip Pattern Matching",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Output should contain 'head'"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Round-Trip Pattern Matching",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INTEGRATION TESTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Integration test using the canonical recursive factorial function.
This is a small but complete program that exercises pattern
matching, recursion, arithmetic, and the period terminator
together.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Translate and re-emit `factorial(0) -> 1; factorial(N) -> N *
factorial(N - 1).`, assert the regenerated source contains the
function name and the recursive call.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Factorial source -> regenerated preserves recursion, passed
- Generator drops the recursive call -> contains check fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_integration_factorial" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "factorial(0) -> 1; factorial(N) when N > 0 -> N * factorial(N - 1)."

    Note: Complete pipeline
    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module1 be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Let hir_module be translate_erlang_to_hir with module1 of type HIRModuleRecord

    Let module2 be generate_erlang_from_hir with hir_module

    Let output be emit_erlang_module with module2

    Note: Check recursive function preserved
    If not output contains "factorial":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Integration Factorial",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Output should contain 'factorial'"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Integration Factorial",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Integration test using Erlang's actor model (spawn + send + receive)
across a simple counter actor. Exercises concurrency primitives
together with state-update via tail recursion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Translate and re-emit an actor pattern with spawn, !, and receive;
assert the regenerated source preserves all three primitives.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Counter actor source -> regenerated has spawn/!/receive, passed
- Generator drops spawn -> "spawn missing" failure
- Generator changes ! semantics -> failure
@End TestCases

Process called "test_integration_actor_model" returns TestResult:
    Let input be "loop() -> receive {get, Pid} -> Pid ! {value, 42}, loop(); stop -> ok end."

    Let lexer be create_lexer with input
    Call lex with lexer

    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let module1 be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Let hir_module be translate_erlang_to_hir with module1 of type HIRModuleRecord

    Let module2 be generate_erlang_from_hir with hir_module

    Let output be emit_erlang_module with module2

    Note: Check actor pattern preserved
    If not output contains "receive":
        Return a value of type TestResult with
            test_name as "Integration Actor Model",
            passed as false,
            error_message as "Output should contain 'receive'"
    End If

    Return a value of type TestResult with
        test_name as "Integration Actor Model",
        passed as true,
        error_message as ""
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TEST RUNNER
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level orchestrator for the Erlang test suite. Creates a
TestSuite, runs all 19 test_* procs, and collects their TestResults
via add_test_result. Returns the populated suite for the caller
(main) to print via report_test_suite.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. create_test_suite("Erlang Translator").
2. For each test_lexer_*, test_parser_*, test_translator_*,
   test_generator_*, test_emitter_*, test_roundtrip_*,
   test_integration_*: call it, then add_test_result.
3. Return populated suite.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 19 tests pass -> suite.failed_count == 0
- Any test fails -> failed_count >= 1; report_test_suite prints each
@End TestCases

Process called "run_erlang_tests" returns TestSuite:
    Let suite be create_test_suite with "Erlang Translation System"

    Note: Run lexer tests
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_lexer_atoms
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_lexer_variables
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_lexer_numbers
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_lexer_operators
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_lexer_binary_syntax

    Note: Run parser tests
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_parser_simple_function
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_parser_pattern_matching
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_parser_guards
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_parser_case_expression
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_parser_receive_block
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_parser_list_comprehension

    Note: Run translator tests
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_translator_basic_function
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_translator_message_passing

    Note: Run generator tests
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_generator_basic_function

    Note: Run emitter tests
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_emitter_module

    Note: Run round-trip tests
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_roundtrip_simple_function
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_roundtrip_pattern_matching

    Note: Run integration tests
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_integration_factorial
    Call add_test_result with suite and test_integration_actor_model

    Return suite
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MAIN ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Entry point. Runs the suite and prints the report. Exits with a
zero or non-zero status conventionally would belong here but the
return type is Nothing so the exit code is implicit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Call run_erlang_tests -> suite.
2. Call report_test_suite(suite) -> report.
3. Print report.
@End Implementation

Process called "main" returns Nothing:
    Let suite be run_erlang_tests

    Let report be report_test_suite with suite

    Note: Print report (simplified - in production would use IO)
    Note: Report output would be displayed here
End Process
